    "reasoning": "The task requires implementing a 16-bit register with byte-enable functionality and synchronous reset. I'll break this down into steps:\n\n1. The module has 16 D flip-flops (FFs) storing 16-bit data.\n2. Each FF is controlled by byteena signals:\n   - byteena[1] controls upper byte d[15:8]\n   - byteena[0] controls lower byte d[7:0]\n3. On each positive clock edge, the data is registered with enable control.\n4. resetn is active-low synchronous reset.\n\nTo avoid syntax errors:\n- All signals must be declared as 'logic'\n- Sequential logic uses 'always @(posedge clk)' with proper reset handling\n- Byte enable logic needs to handle assignment correctly using conditional assignments\n- No implicit sensitivity lists in always blocks except for combinational logic\n\nImplementation approach:\n- Use two always blocks: one for sequential logic (register updates) and one for combinational logic (byte enable handling)\n- Create internal 16-bit register signal to hold the data\n- In sequential block, update the register based on byteena and reset conditions\n- Assign the register to output q\n\nKey considerations:\n- When resetn is low, all bits should be set to 0\n- When byteena[1] is high, update upper byte (d[15:8])\n- When byteena[0] is high, update lower byte (d[7:0])\n- Ensure proper bit selection without reverse indexing issues",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input clk,\n    input resetn,\n    input [1:0] byteena,\n    input [15:0] d,\n    output [15:0] q\n);\n\n    // Internal 16-bit register to store the data\n    logic [15:0] reg_q;\n\n    // Sequential logic for registering the data\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (!resetn) begin\n            reg_q <= 16'b0;\n        end else begin\n            // Update upper byte if byteena[1] is high\n            if (byteena[1])\n                reg_q[15:8] <= d[15:8];\n            \n            // Update lower byte if byteena[0] is high\n            if (byteena[0])\n                reg_q[7:0] <= d[7:0];\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Output assignment\n    assign q = reg_q;\n\nendmodule"
